SIMPLE: discountenance
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Discountenance
<hw>Dis*coun"te*nance</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Discountenanced</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Discountenancing</conjf>
<pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>dis-</ets> +
<ets>countenance</ets>: cf. OF. <ets>descontenancer</ets>, F.
<ets>d⟦eacute⟧contenancer</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To ruffle or
discompose the countenance of; to put of countenance; to put to shame;
to abash.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How would one look from his majestic brow . . . ⟦br⟧
<qex>Discountenance</qex> her despised!</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The hermit was somewhat <qex>discountenanced</qex> by this
observation.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To refuse to countenance, or give the support of
one's approval to; to give one's influence against; to restrain by cold
treatment; to discourage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A town meeting was convened to <qex>discountenance</qex> riot.</q>
<rj><qau>Bancroft.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Discountenance</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Discountenance
<hw>Dis*coun"te*nance</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Unfavorable aspect;
unfriendly regard; cold treatment; disapprobation; whatever tends to
check or discourage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He thought a little <qex>discountenance</qex> on those persons
would suppress that spirit.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Discountenancer</ent>⟦br⟧
